  <static seed="46" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicMath/FractionsCalculation/MultiplyThreeFractions30.pg">
    <statement><p>Multiply: <m>\displaystyle{ {{\frac{15}{2}}} \cdot {{\frac{1}{9}}} \cdot {14} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{35}{3}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>When we multiply fractions, if there is an integer, we change the integer to a fraction by writing <m>1</m> as its denominator. For example, <m>14 = \frac{14}{1}</m>.</p>
<p>When multiplying with fractions, reduce numerators and denominators if possible. This way, we can avoid dealing with big numbers.</p>
<p>The full computation is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {{\frac{15}{2}}} \cdot {{\frac{1}{9}}} \cdot {14}
        \amp = {{\frac{15}{2}}} \cdot {{\frac{1}{9}}} \cdot \frac{14}{1} \\
        \amp = \frac{5\cdot3}{1 \cdot2} \cdot \frac{1}{3\cdot3} \cdot \frac{2\cdot7}{1} \\
        \amp = \frac{5}{1} \cdot \frac{1}{3} \cdot \frac{7}{1} \\
        \amp = {{\frac{35}{3}}} \\
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
</solution>
